Probably Verginius argued that Caeso could not become a citizen of Etruria and therefore was still a citizen of Rome, for it was the law that a man who went into banish- ment did not cease to be a citizen of Rome until he was ad- mitted to the citizenship of another state.

sollemne. Annus prob. contains the root amb (am) which appears in ἀμφὶ, ambire, dcc. sollus was an old Latin word (Gk, ὅλος) which appears also in sollers, solidus, solliferreum (sc. telum). Sollemnis therefore means recurring every year, and secondarily that which ought to recur every year, stated, regular. It was used specially in connexion with the regular, stated festivals of the Roman religion, and hence is used by Latin writers in two shades of meaning according as the re- ligious connexion of the word, or the sense of regular recur- rence, is predominant in the mind of the writer. Here it is qualified by in singulos annos (showing that the dcrivation had been lost sight of) and means ‘a regular annual institution!
